1. Signature and return
Number.isInteger(value) -> boolean
Returns true if value is a number and is an integer (no fractional component); otherwise false.

2. Semantics and edge cases
- Returns false for NaN, Infinity, -Infinity
- Returns false for non-number types (strings, booleans, arrays)
- Returns true for floating point values that represent integer values due to IEEE-754 precision (e.g., 5.0)
- For very large numbers near Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER, precision loss may cause unexpected true results for non-integers

3. Polyfill and equivalent implementation
Equivalent check: typeof value === 'number' && isFinite(value) && Math.floor(value) === value
This pattern handles NaN and Infinity and uses Math.floor to detect fractional part; note behavior with negative numbers uses floor so compare against truncation where appropriate.

4. Examples and numeric precision notes
- Number.isInteger(0) -> true
- Number.isInteger(0.1) -> false
- Number.isInteger(5.0000000000000001) -> true due to representational precision

